\begin_layout Standard
The rise of Big Data analytics over unstructured text has led to renewed
 interest in information extraction (IE).
 These applications need effective IE as a first step towards solving end-to-end
 real world problems (e.g.
 biology, medicine, finance, media and entertainment, etc).
 Much recent NLP research has focused on addressing specific IE problems
 using a pipeline of multiple machine learning techniques.
 This approach requires an analyst with the expertise to answer questions
 such as: “What ML techniques should I combine to solve this problem?”;
 “What features will be useful for the composite pipeline?”; and “Why is
 my model giving the wrong answer on this document?”.
 The need for this expertise creates problems in real world applications.
 It is very difficult in practice to find an analyst who both understands
 the real world problem and has deep knowledge of applied machine learning.
 As a result, the real impact by current IE research does not match up to
 the abundant opportunities available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this tutorial, we introduce the concept of transparent machine learning.
 A transparent ML technique is one that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
produces models that a typical real world use can read and understand;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
uses algorithms that a typical real world user can understand; and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
allows a real world user to adapt models to new domains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tutorial is aimed at IE researchers in both the academic and industry
 communities who are interested in developing and applying transparent ML.
\end_layout

